{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st century Philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''James McEvoy''' |birth_date = 14 October 1943 |birth_place = [[Larne, Northern Ireland]] |death_date = 2 October 2010 |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Thomism]] | institutions = [[National University of Ireland]] |main_interests = | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1974 | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = [[Philipp Rosemann]] |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[Université catholique de Louvain|University of Louvain]] (Ph.D.), [[Queen’s University of Belfast]] (M.A.) |influences = [[Aquinas]], [[Bonaventure]], [[Anselm of Canterbury]], [[Thomas Gallus]], [[Peter of Ireland]], [[Eriugena]], [[Robert Grosseteste]] |influenced = |awards = }}
'''James McEvoy''' (14 October 1943 in [[Larne, Northern Ireland]] - 2 October 2010) was an Irish [[philosopher]] and priest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Death of James McEvoy|url=https://grossetestesociety.org/2010/10/16/rev-prof-james-mcevoy/|website=[[International Robert Grosseteste Society]]|accessdate=23 April 2018|date=16 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=James McEvoy 1943-2010|journal=[[The International Journal of the Platonic Tradition]]|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/docserver/18725082/v5n1_s1.pdf?expires=1524394441&id=id&accname=guest&checksum=D4298C5DA29A810B4A96A5EF81FA1440|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=McEvoy|first1=J. J.|title=Amor Amicitiae|date=2004|publisher=Peeters Publishers|isbn=9789042913950|pages=11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rMZB8KFSKV8C&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=james+mcevoy+rosemann+thesis+louvaine&source=bl&ots=0QPxP5zbkm&sig=0oeWRQlIJFvW5d8JLWQ6yyzuCn8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSz6Xs1c3aAhWoiKYKHckxClAQ6AEIMDAC#v=onepage&q=james%20mcevoy%20rosemann%20thesis%20louvaine&f=false|language=en}}</ref> He was the emeritus professor of [[scholastic philosophy]] at [[Queen’s University Belfast]].
